Although highly qualified black faculty members are frequently lured to top-rated institutions by lucrative offers and incentives, there are many who experience isolation and alienation in the academic environment, where their numbers are minuscule.

Until black faculty and administrators are more visible on our campuses, particularly in decision-making positions, colleges will perpetuate an ominous example - one that graduates may carry to the workplace and the community. Colleges and universities are centers of power. The examples set today will shape the attitudes of tomorrow's leaders. RUDOLPH A. CAIN Associate Professor of Education Empire State College State University of New York Brooklyn